Research the multi-language parity problem in static analysis: which code quality rules should apply uniformly across all programming languages versus which must be language-specific, and how do major tools handle this distinction. Compare the rule sets of SonarQube, Semgrep, and CodeClimate across Python, Java, JavaScript, TypeScript, Go, Ruby, PHP, C#, C++, and Rust. For each tool, identify which rules exist in all language plugins versus which are language-exclusive. Categorize rules by type: complexity rules (are the cyclomatic thresholds the same for Go vs Java?), naming convention rules (PEP 8 vs Google Java Style), documentation rules (docstrings vs Javadoc vs GoDoc), error handling rules (checked exceptions vs Result types vs error returns), and null safety rules (NullPointerException patterns vs Option/Maybe patterns). Research the SonarQube Language Plugins architecture to understand how rule parity is maintained or intentionally broken across languages. Also research the Roslyn Analyzer ecosystem for C# and whether its rules have equivalents in other language ecosystems. The practical goal is to produce a policy matrix defining which of the 40+ analyzers in Heimdall Quality should have per-language variants versus a single shared implementation, and where the rule logic fundamentally differs by language paradigm.
